How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time were in most cases selling trips only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even to socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered in those times trips to the West, but one had to put in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, it wasn't all won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs bought. This custom still persists.
The Czechs' way of travelling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries all over the world.
There is no great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that Croatia, the currently favourite destination, until 1989, could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris Czech groups slept in the parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or a pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take with them food (conservatives, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it also average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, the agencies began to prepare travel regularly from 1997 on, using charter flights connections, which caused travel prices to drop incredibly compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90th century, Czechs were travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
From that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting close to 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech kroner per head on trips abroad, including expenses on the stay site.
