While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time preceding his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realized that it wasn't that hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the UK DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's personal information stash is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision - the way vendors have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
Arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way to do an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not at all surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry with immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stand behind the computer screen."
DEMOS's work is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an upsurge in research, driving the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go through the game, and they'd never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study conducted by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that university students who talked about their drinking exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many status updates with their drunkards.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Child Health, Behavior and Development Center at Seattle's Institute for Child Research, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinking" its own population for data.
The site's Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - advocates of digital freedom long ago claiming that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be looking at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study that he conducted with the student Facebook public walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
