7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, shown in a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius from technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered Job interview that has been dusted as an advance of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flow diagram yonki - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new NeXT computer company, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after the death of Jobs that a full copy was discovered in VHS in the director's garage.
This slightly reissued archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Job's perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to move faster towards the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there is something raw and inspiring about the Jobs that we see here, the dreamer anxious at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers that give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
