Jobs takes to detail their efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Disconcerted by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done with a good cover eye, and which was then adjusted with a "variable" - it developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the Pope's joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" that he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
It has been written extensively about the device, but the euphoria of Jobs here describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and you were screaming through the pay phone and going back a minute later to the pay phone next door," says Jobs with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
We both didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into jeopardy just before the Pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs obtained a part-time summer job in Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desk computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode-tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for her.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the move.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of base plates, a client asked him if he could assemble the entire team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while in Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
