Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of his market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, so what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up leading companies and people in charge of products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position is rotted by people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
Much is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make the electrons, the glass makes them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything is reduced to taste - it is reduced to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to those things that you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing big ideas.
What made Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were by chance the best computer scientists in the world.
