How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each party accuses of lying to the other.
The administrators of Pennsylvania State University have been accused of perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolás Sarkozy was "pilled" with an open microphone affirming US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
The New York Congressman and Internet exhibitor, Anthony Weiner, made a mockery of his denials quickly rebutted by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with infractions in campaign funding related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends of traps in school and university examinations are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given the answers of the exams to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been rebutted.
The liars do look into their eyes.
They don't always stutter, babbling, blush, or restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years canvassing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "minority oriented towards themselves," while women say more lies "directed towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than non-married people (but the lies they usually say tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty when you lie to him.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the posture of the subject, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's best that you know if someone normally hits his foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when he sees his feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture meaningfully, or display a "post-interview relief" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely show that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up and used the past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distance language: "I did not have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when they answer a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... until I understand it."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the possibilities of anyone to avoid being victimized by the con artists in their professional and personal lives.
