The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of this year's election process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on 9 November, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution or Electoral Code of the State or its Electoral Justice Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the completion of the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the current electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted to publish them within the deadlines provided for in the State Newspaper Act, arguing that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislature and called the state's representative's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal", since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may take place on the assumption that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and calculation in the file of the box or does not work in the possession of the president of the same; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations in the records.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the boxes of the election may be made where there is evidence that the difference between the candidate presumed winner of the election in question and the candidate who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition who applied for the second of the nominated candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the candidate allegedly winning and the candidate second is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case electoral packages which have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation there is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16 percent, but without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
