Any blockage or delay in their efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure to warn that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
You'll end your round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister will succeed.
To rescue Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
