Fujimori is interned again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his head doctor reported.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from a number of illnesses, including cancer in the language for which he has been operated four times and remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Channel N of television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he did not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated on four times from cancer to the tongue, he has a weight loss of 18 kilos that has been combined with other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreas cyst, kidney stones, hypertension, and leg circulatory problems, the doctor enumerated.
Fujimori has been in detention since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official committee, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin a visit to Mexico this Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with her Mexican partner, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "a propriety for the exchange of information in all political matters between the two nations", according to the President of the South American country on his website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's rejection and the call to consult its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group composed of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to emerge from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) "grey list", made up of countries that did not implement all international standards of tax cooperation.
At the commercial level, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The bigoted plumber passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has struggled, tirelessly, over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had he done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which comes this month to stores all over the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows playing in three dimensions without the need to use glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how the stereoscopy without glasses should work," said Nintendo's specialist press officer in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game originally designed for that support", since so far successes such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesperson has argued that despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez has said that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to engage less skilled users.
Once overtaken, the most experts will be able to give a "second turn" to the levels of play, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
