Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven more people lost their lives.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others lost their lives indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in full structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were the right ones to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the staff.
In addition, he said that investigations in the impact zone do not report the appearance of pieces in the field.
"In one search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The helicopter design was for 19 passengers, with adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary assured that it is a priority to have the results before possible; however, the investigation can last for several months, it could even reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Staff operated at cruising speed and that this happened on a soft ascending terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, SCT leader Pérez Jácome listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was conducted under visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM found conditions suitable for take-off, as the aircraft moved towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, cloud layers were present at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloud conditions the crew sought a lower elevation area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and side-by-side trajectory.
The pattern of dispersal of the aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter was impacted in the field under structural integrity conditions.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the crash site, there is still no evidence on the ship's remains of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,000,200 feet above the mid-sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was expected to disarticulate along this route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After thorough search in a larger area than the tuned site, around the accident, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Leads Social Security research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Childhood and Adolescents' protocol, which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center XXI century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population is invited to participate whether or not it is entitled to participate, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico Orient).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Sports Morelos Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he stated that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (the aim is to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,' said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity results in the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which makes it possible to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the television and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the bumps could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
At his conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and therefore the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, some of them of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called Maltese, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, he abounded, placing a last layer called rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
Since it is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also needs to have the right thickness and care should be taken for the material it is made of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only after it affects the asphalt folder, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researcher System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, in order to prevent frequent bumps from forming.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow repair of bumps with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
