So it was the work of the calenian who identified Alfonso Cano's corpse.
A lophoscopist from Cali passed into history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
Last November 4th a Lophoscopist of the CTI of Cali passed into history as the man who confirmed the identity of the highest leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", through the collation of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the CTI section, Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years, was on the turn of "availability".
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to stay for more than five days in the jungle to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of the hands and feet.
The week of operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's death card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed like a local peasant, no glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those of the card.
His eye didn't fail: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the chief of the FARC.
In search of the footprint
For a typist from the Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Typhyloscopy is an accurate science, without any margin of error, that can become key to the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When they are captured, many criminals present false ballots or do not have papers.
We take the fingerprint and search them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a theft case, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because at that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to make a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the print from all hands and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently they found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle coincided.
Although this doesn't guarantee he was the killer, it does place him at the crime scene.
A CTI typist explained that in objects "prints are removed with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the TV program CSI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective collage is performed.
