Canadians live by denying death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls on Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Canadian society continues to deny death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they wish to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient proposes this option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
For starters, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death."
On medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, although most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Let us remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia, as they believe that it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, as indicated by an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66 per cent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
As for those who have experienced assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents felt that a trial should not be initiated against them.
Regarding the maintenance or interruption of a patient's health care, the situation is not so clear, as the authors of the report indicate.
Furthermore, its recommendations suggest that the Criminal Code should indicate that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient rejects end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls on Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and subjected to the same procedures.
