Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investment.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without complete democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to the disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for European economic governance.
So be it.
But thinking about it without greater political and democratic integration, and without being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and lead us to a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson remains applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
Only by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European popular sovereignty, can we be achieved.
To build Europe, let's make Europe.
Cards with "no contact" chip are generalized
The world chip card lounge starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart cabinet calculations.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or purchases simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year will be sold worldwide 460 million cards with no contact chip, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to continue to increase in 2012 (an estimated 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has been lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa banking cards already have this feature, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa cards are being used without contact.
But the large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million MasterCard Pass cards without contact this year.
To put the top gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have committed themselves to systematically disseminating non-contact banking cards to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France.
Banks Test Mobile Payment
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
At present, there are few devices equipped with the Near Field Communication (NFC) technology, which is essential for making transactions.
"They're falling behind."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We expect between 80 and 120 million units to be sold in 2012 worldwide," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Crédit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones will be equipped with around 200 customers and collaborators with a cover that allows the payment without contact.
The OPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseilles.
And the Société General has also stated yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile phone.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, which had long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even said that Algiers already "has certainty."
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the catwalks.
Kidnapped in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The survey of calls indicates several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues especially captured the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or his operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pushing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as an illumined community of unworthy interest.
A Fast Success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist magnet Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for the sharia, while its militants launch themselves into the struggle against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily directed to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were especially active and attacks on police stations increased.
Abuya's reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has been radicalized and abandoned its northern feuds.
Last Christmas, he claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, particularly the police protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is a source of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
