Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects directly Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year to Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km connecting the Saint Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents the air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land transit through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom's managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream society.
It was also necessary to extend measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs about 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project leaders gave up the control platform, seeing that the Swedish were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to establish itself permanently at sea off their coasts.
"In case of failure, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the pipeline's condition is ensured by means of an underwater robot, carried out by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one metre, and moves with gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any need for repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
To it, the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the entire gas transport capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of 25 years.
"Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas you actually transport," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves with a height of 4.5 metres form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
In total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back their taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, from hours of writing to the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine books with the present look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, took charge of the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of people with disabilities are seeking employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the entire population.
Disappointing?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It should be mentioned that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years of age (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality is advancing, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité indicated that the directors surveyed had "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with "excessive representation of persons in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
